<p id="Par25" class="p">The 
 <italic class="italic">state model</italic> has a simple formulation in terms of initial occurrence probability, i.e., at 
 <italic class="italic">t</italic> = 1, which we will designate 
 <italic class="italic">μ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">z,s,t</italic> = 1
 </sub>. The initial occurrence states are assumed to be 
 <italic class="italic">independent identically distributed</italic> Bernoulli random variables, denoted as z
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">s</italic>,
  <italic class="italic">t</italic> = 1
 </sub> ~ Bernoulli(
 <italic class="italic">μ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">z,s,t</italic> = 1
 </sub>). In all subsequent periods, the occurrence state 
 <italic class="italic">z</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">s,t</italic> + 1
 </sub> is a Bernoulli trial with a success parameter 
 <italic class="italic">μ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">z,s,t</italic> + 1
 </sub> that depends on whether cell 
 <italic class="italic">s</italic> was occupied in period 
 <italic class="italic">t</italic> and on the value of two parameters that indicate either the probability of extinction, 
 <italic class="italic">p</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">φ</italic>
 </sub>, or colonization, 
 <italic class="italic">p</italic>
 <sub class="sub">
  <italic class="italic">γ</italic>
 </sub>, so that:
 <disp-formula id="Equ2" class="disp-formula">
